item.title: RBA Review Panelist Says Reforms Won't Undermine Central Bank Governor
item.description: One of the architects of a recent review of the Reserve Bank of Australia’s operations said proposed changes won’t undermine the power of the governor, in response to claims that critical decisions would be in the hands of part-time board members.

item.title: Investec Forecasts Solid Rise in Profits
item.description: Investec expects to report first-half adjusted profits of up to £450 million, driven by strong results in the U.K. and South Africa, and sees its return on equity meeting its guidance.

item.title: Ten-Year Bund Yield Remains Near Year-to-Date High
item.description: Eurozone government bond yields were little changed, with the 10-year Bund yield within the 2.70%-2.80% range that SEB Research targeted for the third and fourth quarters of the year.

item.title: Microsoft's Activision Deal Clears Main Hurdle as U.K. Regulator Accepts Changes
item.description: The U.K. Competition and Markets Authority said a new deal submitted by Microsoft should lessen any harm to competition in cloud gaming.

item.title: Sanofi Faces Third-Quarter Forex Hit
item.description: Sanofi estimates a currency impact on third-quarter business earnings per share of 8.5%-9.5% and expects sales to reduce by up to 8.5%.

item.title: U.S. 10-Year Treasury Yield Could Rise Further, Charts Show
item.description: The U.S. 10-year Treasury yield was highly likely to rise further over the next two months, based on technical charts, UOB said.

item.title: Microsoft's Revised Activision Deal Lessons U.K. Competition Concerns
item.description: The U.K. antitrust authority said the new deal submitted by Microsoft addresses competition concerns in cloud gaming, and it opened a consultation on residual concerns it has before making a final decision on the acquisition.

item.title: U.K. Retail Sales Rebound; Still May Disappoint
item.description: Retail-sales volumes rose 0.4% in August, slightly below expectations, after food stores bounced back following wet weather in the prior month.

item.title: Nikkei Falls 0.5%, Dragged by Retail, Pharma Stocks
item.description: Japanese stocks ended lower, dragged by falls in retail and pharmaceutical stocks, as concerns persist about inflation and higher borrowing costs.

item.title: An Insurance Regulator Asked for a Favor. It Cost a Senior Executive His Job.
item.description: Prudential’s CFO resigned after he tried to help line up a job for a regulator’s relative.

item.title: Dollar Could Benefit From Weak European PMI Data
item.description: The dollar will likely benefit from weak eurozone and U.K. PMI data, ING said, while the rise in Treasury yields after the Fed signalled rates would remain higher for longer also supports the greenback.

item.title: China's Economic Worries Spur a Different Kind of Shopping Spree
item.description: Mainland tourists are flocking to Hong Kong in search of investment-focused insurance. One of the big beneficiaries: HSBC.

item.title: Amazon's New Challenge: Bargain Retailers That Are Playing a Different Game
item.description: The e-commerce giant is weighing how to respond to the growing threat from two competitors offering bargain goods.

item.title: Survivors in Flood-Ravaged Libya Wonder if They Will Ever Have a Home Again
item.description: More than 43,000 people have been displaced after their homes were damaged or destroyed.

item.title: South Korean Opposition Leader on Hunger Strike Faces Arrest
item.description: Lawmakers voted to lift immunity for Lee, whom prosecutors allege committed offenses including breach of trust and bribery.

item.title: How U.S. Households Got Turned Upside Down by Higher Interest Rates
item.description: A new reality has finally started to set in across American households: Higher interest rates are here to stay.

item.title: TikTok Fights Threats of More Bans Around the World
item.description: Africa is a new hot spot for the world’s most popular app as governments fear sexual content and extremism.

item.title: When a Congressman Challenged Disney on China, It Laid Off Beijing Staff
item.description: Disney’s China layoffs led to technical malfunctions and delayed efforts to troubleshoot.

item.title: Venice Fights to Save Itself From Tourists
item.description: Venice has long struggled with the impact of mass tourism, but residents say the city has reached a tipping point, accelerated by a boom in European and U.S. tourism.

item.title: What This $6 Billion Rail Line in Laos Reveals About China's Future
item.description: A China-built rail line in Laos aims to jumpstart the country’s exports and provide China a key link to overseas markets. WSJ explores the ambition behind the $6 billion project—part of China’s Belt and Road Initiative—and the economic implications for the region.
